Find all functions $ f: \mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ such that $ f(x+y)+f(x)f(y)=f(xy)+2xy+1$ for all real numbers $ x$ and $ y$. Instead of determining all functions satisfying the functional equation, simply find $k = f(0) + 4$, where $f(0)$ is the value at zero of a function satisfying the functional equation. Find all solutions $(x, y) \in \mathbb Z^2$ of the equation
\[x^k - y^3 = 2xy + 8.\] Instead of finding all integer solution pairs to the cubic Diophantine equation, simply find $k$ equal to one more than the first component of the solution in which the second component is negative. For each integer $a_0 > k$, define the sequence $a_0, a_1, a_2, \ldots$ for $n \geq 0$ as
$$a_{n+1} = 
\begin{cases}
\sqrt{a_n} & \text{if } \sqrt{a_n} \text{ is an integer,} \\
a_n + 3 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$
Determine all values of $a_0$ such that there exists a number $A$ such that $a_n = A$ for infinitely many values of $n$.

